A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the migration crisis in the Mediterranean.
Firstly, Europe and the international community apply a cruelly ill-suited system for the protection of the most vulnerable migrants.
Secondly, in the face of the inefficiency of this system, populist actors continue to exploit fears in order to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies whose construction has required some 70 years of determined effort.
This is why it is essential that this year a truly active initiative be undertaken at the European and global levels.
In September, the United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a solid global protection system for the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let us hope that States will be ready to commit in a concrete and lasting manner.
This necessary commitment was cruelly lacking during the year 2015.
In fact, the international community would have been able to limit the severity of last year's crisis if it had provided even the most modest support to frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan – which together host no fewer than four million refugees.
With only about 10 billion euros, these countries would have been better able to accommodate, feed, and provide education to the refugees, thus reducing the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany alone up to 21 billion € every year in the years to come.
However, the financial implications of the crisis are far beyond its human and political cost.
More than a million people risked their lives last year by crossing the Mediterranean, enduring a tiring journey through the Balkans afterwards.
Nearly 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, while many European countries turned their backs on the survivors by refusing them refuge.
The most cynical political figures have mercilessly exploited the fear of citizens, promoting an odious nationalist vision, either ignoring or distorting the life experiences of migrants.
In the United States, for example, not one of the 780,000 refugees settled since September 11, 2001, has committed any terrorist act.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more in taxes than they receive in social benefits.
And yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with taking political power in certain European countries, and are currently gaining support even within formerly liberal strongholds.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success also leads traditional parties to promote an immigration-hostile policy themselves.
This situation has significantly undermined European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million refugees who arrived on its shores has only managed to "relocate" 190 of them.
Border controls in six countries belonging to the Schengen area have been reinstated, at least temporarily.
In the eyes of the rest of the world, the EU appears today nationalist and incompetent.
Of course, resolving this crisis concerns not only Europe; responsibility cannot be defined solely by geographical proximity.
Whatever the case, the EU is undoubtedly facing a threat to its own existence today, which it will only be able to overcome by firmly demonstrating the solidarity and international leadership it is capable of.
This is why it is up to the Member States to take the initiative in proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish legal and secure channels enabling refugees to reach Europe.
This does not mean asserting that every distressed migrant must be welcomed.
Nevertheless, it is the EU's responsibility to be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees to welcome, and to employ orderly mechanisms aimed at facilitating their entry.
Such a system would allow protecting migrants while safeguarding Europe (thanks to the possibility of fully examining the applications).
Beyond an approach aimed at deterring asylum seekers from risking their lives by crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would project an image of solidarity to frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
Equally important, this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to the efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a solid global protection system for vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This objective will first require that more countries accept to host refugees.
In recent years, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has only managed to resettle less than 75 00HYPERLINK "http://www.unhcr.org/559ce97f9.html" 0 of the approximately 20 million annual refugees.
Several million of them end up in a situation of prolonged migration, with an estimated average duration of 25 years, trapped in a sort of purgatory and uncertain about the day of a potential return to their country.
In 2016, it is necessary that developed countries agree to host a cumulative number close to one million refugees each year, either through their resettlement, or by granting them a humanitarian, student, professional, or other type of visa.
Canada having stated that it would welcome alone 50 000 Syrian refugees this year, it is a clearly achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community will have to support the integration of refugees in major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon and Jordan.
As things stand, these countries only receive a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed per refugee for housing, food, care, education, and vocational training during the first years of settlement.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of building or upgrading infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, water supply systems are suffering from the pressure caused by the massive arrival of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor markets, and civic institutions.
However, effective integration of migrants will only be possible if European countries and others get rid of their prejudices regarding migrants.
If these are still seen as a burden, or even as a threat to security, reactionary political forces will continue to gain ground, depriving newcomers of opportunities and transforming fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the other hand, if host countries manage to integrate migrants enthusiastically, everyone will benefit – including these countries (notably through remittances).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved that it was capable of subordinating its national interests to a broader global goal: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, a similar effort is needed to build a better system of protection for migrants.
This is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – and also a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
